Savveyra Architecture Specification
Events, Proposals & Quotations
Version 1.0 (Architecture Baseline)
________________________________________
1. Purpose
This document defines the architecture governing the interaction between Events, Kitchen Proposals and Sales Quotations.
It establishes ownership, responsibilities, workflows and business rules that implementation must follow.
This document is authoritative for this section of Savveyra. Database design, Appsmith implementation and future development must conform to these principles.
________________________________________
2. Core Philosophy
Savveyra separates operational food production from customer sales.
Kitchen and Sales work together but remain independent business domains.
Both domains operate on the same Event but own different business objects.
The system must preserve this separation while allowing collaboration.
________________________________________
3. Primary Business Objects
Customer
Represents the customer or organisation requesting the Event.
A Customer may have multiple Contacts.
A Customer may participate in many Events.
________________________________________
Contact
Represents an individual person.
A Contact may belong to multiple Customers.
A Contact may also act as the Customer.
Customer Contact is optional.
________________________________________
Venue
Represents where the Event will occur.
A Venue may have multiple Venue Contacts.
________________________________________
Venue Contact
Represents a person at the Venue.
Venue Contact is optional.
________________________________________
Event
An Event represents one operational catering job.
The Event is the parent container for all Kitchen Proposals and Sales Quotations relating to that job.
An Event may exist without any Proposal.
An Event may exist without any Quotation.
Kitchen-only Events are valid.
________________________________________
Proposal
A Proposal represents one complete operational version of an Event prepared by Kitchen.
A Proposal is not simply a menu.
A Proposal is a complete snapshot of the Event at the moment it is created.
Multiple Proposals may exist for the same Event.
Each Proposal represents an independent operational option.
________________________________________
Quotation
A Quotation represents the customer-facing commercial document prepared by Sales.
A Quotation originates from a Proposal.
Multiple Quotation revisions may exist.
Quotation revisions preserve customer communication history.
________________________________________
4. Ownership Principle
This is a fundamental architectural rule.
Permissions control actions. Ownership controls business rules.
Permissions never transfer ownership.
Ownership determines:
•	lifecycle 
•	statuses 
•	workflows 
•	business rules 
•	downstream behaviour 
Permissions determine only:
•	who may view 
•	who may create 
•	who may edit 
•	who may approve 
•	who may perform specific actions 
Even an Administrator does not change ownership.
Editing another department's object does not transfer ownership.
________________________________________
5. Domain Ownership
Kitchen owns:
•	Event operational planning 
•	Proposals 
•	Menus 
•	Kitchen production information 
Sales owns:
•	Quotations 
•	Customer pricing 
•	Customer communication 
•	Quotation revisions 
Customer owns nothing inside the system.
Customer receives Quotation documents only.
________________________________________
6. Event Architecture
The Event is the operational container.
The Event links together:
•	Customer 
•	Contact 
•	Venue 
•	Kitchen 
•	Sales 
•	Proposals 
•	Quotations 
The Event itself does not represent a single proposal.
Instead, the Event contains multiple complete Proposals.
The user decides whether a significantly different request remains the same Event or becomes a new Event.
Savveyra does not force that decision.
________________________________________
7. Proposal Architecture
A Proposal represents one complete operational solution for an Event.
Each Proposal contains a complete snapshot including:
•	Customer 
•	Contact 
•	Venue 
•	Venue Contact 
•	Event Date 
•	Format 
•	Guest Counts 
•	Menus 
•	Menu quantities 
•	Kitchen costs 
•	Deposits (where applicable) 
•	Notes 
•	Kitchen notes 
•	Any other Event information required to reproduce that proposal exactly. 
Nothing inside a Proposal is dynamically linked after it is created.
A Proposal preserves history.
________________________________________
8. Proposal Lifecycle
Proposal Statuses:
Draft
Sent
Accepted
Rejected
________________________________________
Draft
Kitchen may edit freely.
Draft is the only editable Proposal.
________________________________________
Sent
Proposal has been handed to Sales.
Proposal becomes immutable.
No editing is permitted.
________________________________________
Accepted
Sales has accepted and used the Proposal.
Proposal remains immutable.
________________________________________
Rejected
Sales has chosen not to use the Proposal.
Proposal remains immutable.
Rejected Proposals remain part of history.
________________________________________
9. Proposal Revision Philosophy
Once a Proposal has been Sent it is never edited.
If Sales requests changes:
Kitchen creates a new Proposal.
The previous Proposal remains unchanged.
Example:
Proposal 3
↓
Sales requests changes
↓
Kitchen duplicates Proposal 3
↓
Proposal 4 (Draft)
↓
Kitchen edits Proposal 4
↓
Proposal 4 becomes Sent
This preserves complete historical accuracy.
________________________________________
10. Proposal Selection Behaviour
Selecting a Proposal loads that Proposal into the Event workspace.
The Event page reflects the selected Proposal.
Changing Proposal changes:
•	Customer 
•	Contact 
•	Venue 
•	Event Date 
•	Guest Counts 
•	Menus 
•	Notes 
•	Header information 
•	Kitchen information 
The Proposal becomes the current working version displayed by the Event page.
________________________________________
11. Proposal Actions
Draft Proposal
•	Edit 
•	Send 
•	Duplicate 
•	Delete Draft 
Sent Proposal
•	View 
•	Duplicate 
Accepted Proposal
•	View 
•	Duplicate 
Rejected Proposal
•	View 
•	Duplicate 
Duplicate creates the next Proposal number.
Duplicate copies the complete Proposal.
The new Proposal begins as Draft.
________________________________________
12. Quotation Architecture
Quotation is independent from Proposal.
Proposal belongs to Kitchen.
Quotation belongs to Sales.
A Quotation is created from a Proposal.
Quotation revisions preserve customer communication.
Issued Quotations remain historical records.
________________________________________
13. Proposal to Quotation Relationship
Proposal
↓
Sales Review
↓
Quotation
↓
Quotation Revisions
Kitchen never edits Quotations.
Sales never edits Proposals.
Communication occurs through creation of new Proposals.
________________________________________
14. Quotation Revisions
Sales may:
Create new Quotation
Create Quotation Revision
Issue Quotation
Withdraw Quotation
Accept customer response
Decline customer response
These actions belong entirely to Sales.
Kitchen remains unaffected.
________________________________________
15. Snapshot Philosophy
Snapshots are fundamental.
Proposal is a complete snapshot.
Quotation is a complete snapshot.
Historical records must never change.
History is preserved by creating new versions rather than modifying existing ones.
________________________________________
16. Event Change Philosophy
Some customer requests are minor.
Examples:
•	Change menu 
•	Change fish 
•	Increase guests slightly 
These become new Proposals.
Some requests fundamentally change the operational job.
Examples:
•	Different venue 
•	Different service style 
•	Major guest increase 
•	Different function 
The user decides whether:
•	this remains the same Event 
or
•	becomes a new Event. 
Savveyra supports either approach.
________________________________________
17. Kitchen Workflow
Create Event
↓
Create Proposal
↓
Edit Proposal
↓
Send Proposal
↓
Sales Response
↓
If changes required
↓
Duplicate Proposal
↓
Create next Proposal
↓
Send again
Kitchen history remains intact.
________________________________________
18. Sales Workflow
Receive Proposal
↓
Review
↓
Create Quotation
↓
Issue to Customer
↓
Customer feedback
↓
Create Revision if required
↓
Issue again
Quotation history remains intact.
________________________________________
19. Customer Workflow
Customer never interacts with Proposals.
Customer receives Quotations only.
Customer may:
Accept
Decline
Request changes
Requested changes are communicated back to Kitchen by Sales through creation of a new Proposal.
________________________________________
20. Business Rules
1.	Proposal and Quotation are separate business objects. 
2.	Proposal belongs to Kitchen. 
3.	Quotation belongs to Sales. 
4.	Proposal is a complete Event snapshot. 
5.	Quotation is a complete customer snapshot. 
6.	Sent Proposals are immutable. 
7.	Issued Quotations are immutable. 
8.	History is never rewritten. 
9.	New versions are created instead of editing history. 
10.	Permissions never transfer ownership. 
11.	Ownership determines business rules. 
12.	Event is the operational parent. 
13.	An Event may have many Proposals. 
14.	An Event may have many Quotations. 
15.	An Event may exist with no Quotations. 
16.	Kitchen may prepare multiple alternative Proposals. 
17.	Sales may prepare multiple Quotation revisions. 
18.	Proposal numbering is independent from Quotation numbering. 
19.	Proposal status belongs only to Kitchen. 
20.	Quotation status belongs only to Sales. 
21.	Customer never sees Proposals. 
22.	Kitchen never edits Quotations. 
23.	Sales never edits Proposals. 
24.	All Proposal revisions create new Proposal numbers. 
25.	All Quotation revisions preserve customer history. 
26.	The Event page displays the currently selected Proposal. 
27.	Selecting another Proposal changes the displayed Event snapshot. 
28.	The user decides whether a major operational change remains the same Event or becomes a new Event. 
________________________________________
21. Guiding Principle
The architecture is based on one overriding concept:
Kitchen and Sales collaborate through controlled handoff, not shared ownership.
Each domain owns its own business objects.
Each domain preserves its own history.
Each domain follows its own workflow.
Permissions may allow users to work across domains, but ownership, business rules and historical integrity remain permanently separated.
________________________________________

22. Future Architectural Review
The introduction of complete Event Proposal snapshots changes the architectural contract between Events and downstream operational modules.
Current downstream modules were originally designed assuming a single active Event definition.
Following implementation of the Proposal architecture, all downstream modules shall be reviewed to determine whether their source should remain the Event itself or the currently selected Proposal snapshot.
The first module requiring review is Groceries.
Current behaviour assumes:
Event
    ↓
Groceries
The intended architecture is expected to become:
Event
    ↓
Selected Proposal
    ↓
Groceries
Groceries should operate from the selected Proposal snapshot rather than attempting to interpret multiple Proposals belonging to an Event.
This review is expected to affect:
•	Supabase tables and relationships 
•	Database functions 
•	Appsmith bindings and page behaviour 
The business purpose of Groceries is not expected to change. Only the source of its operational data will be reviewed to ensure consistency with the Proposal architecture.
This review shall be completed after the Event–Proposal–Quotation implementation has been finalised.

